<DOC><DOCNO> AP880812-0109 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-12-88 1248EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--BoatPeople     08-12 0149</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Boat People,0153</SECOND><HEAD>Five Vietnamese Boat People Returning Home Voluntarily</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Five Vietnamese who fled to Hong Kong by boatleft the British colony voluntarily for home Friday, the governmentreported.   About 23,000 boat people remain in Hong Kong camps, includingabout 90 others who have asked to be sent back to the communistnation, about 500 miles to the south.   The Vietnamese who arrived before June 16 are viewed aspolitical refugees eligible for resettlement in third countries.   But under a new policy to curb the surging number of arrivals,the about 7,000 boat people who arrived since mid-June areclassified as illegal immigrants subject to repatriation unlessthey can prove political persecution.   Vietnam said it will accept people who volunteer to return.   The five repatriated Vietnamese men arrived in the same boat inDecember. No reason was given for their decision to return.</TEXT></DOC>